# Wikipedia page: "Net neutrality in the United States" — FCC rule changes, state preemption, edit wars over policy framing
{"eventId":"evt_nn_001","eventType":"claim_first_seen","claimId":"clm_nn_001","fromRevisionId":1280000401,"toRevisionId":1280000402,"section":"Background","before":"","after":"Net neutrality is the principle that internet service providers (ISPs) must treat all data on the internet equally, without discriminating or charging differentially by user, content, website, platform, application, or method of communication. The term was coined by Columbia Law School professor Tim Wu in 2003.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The net neutrality definition and Tim Wu attribution first appeared in this revision.","detail":"Added with citation to Wu, T. (2003), 'Network Neutrality, Broadband Discrimination,' Journal of Telecommunications and High Technology Law."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Established the canonical definition and origin attribution for the article.","confidence":0.95,"discussionType":"origin_claim"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-01-08T10:15:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_002","eventType":"claim_reworded","claimId":"clm_nn_002","fromRevisionId":1280000403,"toRevisionId":1280000404,"section":"FCC rulemaking","before":"The FCC adopted the Open Internet Order in 2015 under Chairman Tom Wheeler, classifying broadband ISPs as common carriers under Title II of the Communications Act.","after":"On February 26, 2015, the FCC adopted the Open Internet Order (FCC 15-24) in a 3-2 party-line vote under Chairman Tom Wheeler. The order reclassified broadband internet access service as a telecommunications service under Title II of the Communications Act of 1934, subjecting ISPs to common-carrier obligations including no blocking, no throttling, and no paid prioritization. The reclassification was upheld by the DC Circuit in United States Telecom Association v. FCC, 825 F.3d 674 (D.C. Cir. 2016), in a 2-1 decision.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a one-sentence summary to include the specific date (Feb 26, 2015), vote count (3-2 party-line), and FCC docket number (15-24).","detail":"Each addition is sourced to the FCC's own order and the DC Circuit's opinion."},{"fact":"The three bright-line rules (no blocking, no throttling, no paid prioritization) were enumerated.","detail":"These are the three core prohibitions in the 2015 Order; specifying them provides substantive content beyond the procedural fact of reclassification."},{"fact":"The DC Circuit's 2016 affirmance was added with citation to the published opinion.","detail":"The judicial affirmance is legally significant because it resolved the statutory classification question at the appellate level."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Enhanced procedural facts with substantive rules and judicial affirmation, providing the legal architecture beyond the headline.","confidence":0.91,"discussionType":"factual_clarification"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-02-15T14:22:10Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_003","eventType":"talk_thread_opened","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000405,"toRevisionId":1280000406,"section":"Talk:Net neutrality in the United States","before":"","after":"The article currently frames the 2015 Order's repeal in 2017 (Restoring Internet Freedom Order) as a simple policy reversal. Several editors have argued this framing is POV by omission — it doesn't address that the 2017 Order was itself challenged under the Administrative Procedure Act (Mozilla v. FCC) and that the 2024 FCC under Chair Rosenworcel voted to restore Title II classification. The article reads as if the policy ended in 2017 when in fact it oscillated across three administrations.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"A new talk page thread titled 'NPOV: repeal-era framing — oscillation, not termination' was opened.","detail":"Started by user TelecomPolicyAnalyst on 2024-04-10T16:45:30Z."},{"fact":"The thread argues that the article's framing implies a single reversal (adopt → repeal) when the actual history is oscillatory (adopt → repeal → restore, with each step litigated).","detail":"The editor cited the 2024 FCC NPRM on Safeguarding and Securing the Open Internet (FCC 24-5) as evidence that the policy trajectory is not linear."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Opened a framing dispute about whether net neutrality policy is a terminated experiment or an oscillatory regulatory cycle.","confidence":0.76,"discussionType":"neutrality_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-04-10T16:45:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_004","eventType":"section_reorganized","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000407,"toRevisionId":1280000408,"section":"Chronology","before":"(A single linear timeline from 2004 to 2018 with subheadings for each FCC action)","after":"(Section reorganized into three eras: 'The classification debate (2004-2014)', 'Title II era (2015-2017)', 'Post-repeal and state action (2018-present)'. Each era has subheadings for FCC actions and judicial review)","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The linear chronology was restructured into three era-level headings with judicial review as a consistent sub-topic.","detail":"The reorganization was proposed by TelecomPolicyAnalyst and adopted after the NPOV discussion reached consensus."},{"fact":"The 'Post-repeal and state action' section was significantly expanded to include California's SB-822, the 2024 FCC NPRM, and the Mozilla v. FCC (2019) remand.","detail":"Previously, state-level net neutrality laws and the 2024 rulemaking were scattered across four different sections."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Restructured from a terminated-experiment narrative to an oscillatory-regulatory-cycle framework.","confidence":0.84,"discussionType":"structure_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-06-05T11:30:20Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_005","eventType":"revert_detected","claimId":"clm_nn_003","fromRevisionId":1280000409,"toRevisionId":1280000410,"section":"Arguments against net neutrality","before":"Opponents of net neutrality regulation argue that it constitutes government overreach into private network management, reduces infrastructure investment, and may violate ISPs' First Amendment rights by compelling speech.","after":"Opponents of net neutrality regulation argue that it constitutes government overreach into private network management, reduces infrastructure investment, and may violate ISPs' First Amendment rights by compelling speech.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"Revision 1280000409 was a revert of revision 1280000408.","detail":"An editor had replaced the balanced opposition summary with 'Net neutrality is a socialist regulatory scheme pushed by big tech companies that want free access to ISPs' infrastructure without paying for it. The free market has always managed network traffic better than federal bureaucrats.' The revert was applied by moderator NeutralTechEditor with summary: 'rv — replacing attributed scholarly arguments with editorial polemic. This is a high-traffic policy page, please review WP:NPOV and WP:ARBCOM.'"}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Restored the attributed opposition-argument summary after polemic editorializing was inserted in wiki voice.","confidence":0.97,"policyDimension":"neutrality","discussionType":"edit_revert"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-07-20T14:10:55Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_006","eventType":"citation_replaced","claimId":"clm_nn_004","fromRevisionId":1280000411,"toRevisionId":1280000412,"section":"State-level net neutrality","before":"California passed SB-822 in 2018, adopting net neutrality rules that were initially blocked by a DOJ lawsuit but subsequently allowed to take effect. [47]","after":"California passed SB-822 (the California Internet Consumer Protection and Net Neutrality Act of 2018), adopting net neutrality rules that were initially blocked by a Department of Justice preemption lawsuit. The Eastern District of California denied California's motion to dismiss the preemption claim in 2019, but the case was stayed pending the resolution of Mozilla v. FCC. After the Mozilla decision rejected the FCC's blanket-preemption argument, the DOJ withdrew its lawsuit in 2021, and the California rules took effect. [47][61][62]","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"Two new citations [61] and [62] were added: the DOJ's notice of voluntary dismissal (Feb 8, 2021) and the California Attorney General's SB-822 regulatory text.","detail":"These provide primary-source documentation of the litigation's resolution."},{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a two-sentence summary to a three-stage litigation narrative (preemption filed → Mozilla stays case → DOJ withdraws).","detail":"This explains the procedural mechanism by which the state law survived, which was opaque in the earlier version."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Clarified the procedural pathway through which California's net neutrality law survived federal preemption challenge.","confidence":0.92,"policyDimension":"verifiability","discussionType":"citation_strengthening"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-09-12T10:55:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_007","eventType":"claim_strengthened","claimId":"clm_nn_005","fromRevisionId":1280000413,"toRevisionId":1280000414,"section":"FCC rulemaking","before":"The FCC under Chair Rosenworcel voted in April 2024 to propose restoring net neutrality rules.","after":"On April 25, 2024, the FCC voted 3-2 under Chair Jessica Rosenworcel to adopt the Safeguarding and Securing the Open Internet Order (FCC 24-52), reclassifying broadband as a Title II telecommunications service and reinstating the bright-line rules against blocking, throttling, and paid prioritization. The order also asserted FCC authority over ISP interconnection arrangements and established a general conduct standard authorizing the FCC to address practices that unreasonably interfere with consumers' ability to access lawful content. As with the 2015 Order, the 2024 Order is expected to face judicial challenge under the Administrative Procedure Act.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was updated from a proposal to an adopted order with specific date, vote count, and docket number.","detail":"FCC 24-52 was adopted in the April 25, 2024 Open Meeting."},{"fact":"Two new regulatory elements were specified: interconnection authority and the general conduct standard.","detail":"These go beyond the three bright-line rules to establish a broader regulatory framework for addressing novel ISP practices."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Updated from a procedural proposal to a substantive order with expanded regulatory scope and forward-looking litigation anticipation.","confidence":0.88,"discussionType":"policy_update"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-10-30T15:40:10Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_008","eventType":"talk_reply_added","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000415,"toRevisionId":1280000416,"section":"Talk:Net neutrality in the United States","before":"(Existing NPOV thread on oscillation framing)","after":"I've drafted a new lede paragraph that frames the policy history as oscillatory: 'Net neutrality policy in the United States has undergone repeated reversals across the Obama, Trump, and Biden administrations, with the FCC adopting Title II classification in 2015, repealing it in 2017, and readopting it in 2024. Each action has been subject to litigation under the Administrative Procedure Act, creating a multi-decade regulatory cycle in which the legal classification of broadband has oscillated between Title I information service and Title II telecommunications service.' This framing avoids implying that any single FCC action was permanent.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"A proposed lede paragraph was posted to the NPOV thread.","detail":"Posted by user TelecomPolicyAnalyst on 2024-11-22T19:30:45Z."},{"fact":"The proposed lede explicitly frames the policy history as an oscillatory cycle with each action subject to litigation.","detail":"This framing is factually accurate — the classification has changed three times in nine years — and avoids the NPOV problem of implying that the most recent action is permanent."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Proposed a lede framing that resolves the NPOV dispute by making the oscillatory nature of the policy the structural narrative rather than an editorial footnote.","confidence":0.78,"discussionType":"dispute_resolution"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-11-22T19:30:45Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_nn_009","eventType":"talk_thread_archived","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000417,"toRevisionId":1280000418,"section":"Talk:Net neutrality in the United States","before":"(Active thread: 'NPOV: repeal-era framing — oscillation, not termination' with 44 replies over 8 months)","after":"(Thread resolved. The article lede now frames the policy history as oscillatory across administrations. A footnote acknowledges that the term 'oscillation' is an editorial periodization choice and links to the talk page discussion for editors who contest this framing.)","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The NPOV thread was closed after the oscillatory-framing lede was adopted by consensus.","detail":"The closing editor was a WikiProject Telecommunications member with no prior involvement in the thread."},{"fact":"The consensus resolution included a footnote mechanism for acknowledging the editorial periodization choice.","detail":"This approach was borrowed from the consensus-resolution footnote on the 'Affordable Care Act' page."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Resolved a framing dispute by making the contested framing explicit and self-documenting rather than pretending to a false objectivity.","confidence":0.81,"discussionType":"dispute_resolution"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2025-01-08T11:00:00Z"}
